os.name: EOL
os.description: The operating system-specific end-of-line marker.

os.name: constants
os.description: Contains commonly used operating system-specific constants for error codes,process signals, and so on.

os.name: devNull
os.description: The platform-specific file path of the null device.

os.name: availableParallelism
os.description: Returns an estimate of the default amount of parallelism a program should use.

os.name: arch
os.description: Returns the operating system CPU architecture for which the Node.

os.name: cpus
os.description: Returns an array of objects containing information about each logical CPU core.

os.name: endianness
os.description: Returns a string identifying the endianness of the CPU for which the Node.

os.name: freemem
os.description: Returns the amount of free system memory in bytes as an integer.

os.name: getPriority
os.description: Returns the scheduling priority for the process specified by pid.

os.name: homedir
os.description: Returns the string path of the current user's home directory.

os.name: hostname
os.description: Returns the host name of the operating system as a string.

os.name: loadavg
os.description: Returns an array containing the 1, 5, and 15 minute load averages.

os.name: machine
os.description: Returns the machine type as a string, such as arm, arm64, aarch64,mips, mips64, ppc64, ppc64le, s390, s390x, i386, i686, x86_64.

os.name: networkInterfaces
os.description: Returns an object containing network interfaces that have been assigned anetwork address.

os.name: platform
os.description: Returns a string identifying the operating system platform for whichthe Node.

os.name: release
os.description: Returns the operating system as a string.

os.name: setPriority
os.description: Attempts to set the scheduling priority for the process specified by pid.

os.name: tmpdir
os.description: Returns the operating system's default directory for temporary files as astring.

os.name: totalmem
os.description: Returns the total amount of system memory in bytes as an integer.

os.name: type
os.description: Returns the operating system name as returned by uname(3).

os.name: uptime
os.description: Returns the system uptime in number of seconds.

os.name: userInfo
os.description: Returns information about the currently effective user.

os.name: version
os.description: Returns a string identifying the kernel version.

os.constants.priority.name: Priority Low
os.constants.priority.description: The lowest process scheduling priority. This corresponds to IDLE_PRIORITY_CLASS on Windows, and a nice value of 19 on all other platforms.

os.constants.priority.name: Priority Below Normal
os.constants.priority.description: The process scheduling priority above PRIORITY_LOW and below PRIORITY_NORMAL. This corresponds to BELOW_NORMAL_PRIORITY_CLASS on Windows, and a nice value of 10 on all other platforms.

os.constants.priority.name: Priority Normal
os.constants.priority.description: The default process scheduling priority. This corresponds to NORMAL_PRIORITY_CLASS on Windows, and a nice value of 0 on all other platforms.

os.constants.priority.name: Priority Above Normal
os.constants.priority.description: The process scheduling priority above PRIORITY_NORMAL and below PRIORITY_HIGH. This corresponds to ABOVE_NORMAL_PRIORITY_CLASS on Windows, and a nice value of -7 on all other platforms.

os.constants.priority.name: Priority High
os.constants.priority.description: The process scheduling priority above PRIORITY_ABOVE_NORMAL and below PRIORITY_HIGHEST. This corresponds to HIGH_PRIORITY_CLASS on Windows, and a nice value of -14 on all other platforms.

os.constants.priority.name: Priority Highest
os.constants.priority.description: The highest process scheduling priority. This corresponds to REALTIME_PRIORITY_CLASS on Windows, and a nice value of -20 on all other platforms.

os.constants.dlopen.description: Perform lazy binding. Node.js sets this flag by default.
Resolve all undefined symbols in the library before dlopen(3) returns.
Symbols defined by the library will be made available for symbol resolution of subsequently loaded libraries.
The converse of RTLD_GLOBAL. This is the default behavior if neither flag is specified.
Make a self-contained library use its own symbols in preference to symbols from previously loaded libraries.
